{"tid":1113921,"cid":4,"subCid":0,"title":"LG喺出咗Android P後嘅第225日 仲未能推出Android P更新","createTime":"2019-04-18T08:01:09.000Z","updateTime":"2019-04-27T08:29:03.000Z","uid":158977,"like":7,"dislike":0,"uniUserReply":10,"replies":[{"pid":"a9613b470691b7293220fef9d0222c5316654024","tid":1113921,"uid":158977,"like":0,"dislike":0,"score":0,"citedBy":0,"replyTime":"2019-04-18T08:01:09.000Z","msg":"LG第一<br />\n<br />\n<br />\n<br />\n更新最慢排第一<img src=\"/assets/faces/normal/sosad.gif\" class=\"hkgmoji\" /><br />\n<br />\nNearly a year ago to the day, <span style=\"color: red;\">LG announced that it was opening an &ldquo;industry-first&rdquo; Software Upgrade Center in an effort to provide better support for its devices over time.</span> With time passed, we can look back at that project and see what a laughable failure it has been, especially looking at Android Pie.<br />\n<br />\nComputerWorld detailed this week just how bad LG has gotten at pushing software updates to its devices. <span style=\"color: red;\">371 days after the Software Upgrade Center opened, it&rsquo;s done basically nothing.</span> True to its word, LG did deliver Android Oreo to the LG G6 (on Verizon) not too long after the center opened, but that was still a whopping nine months after Google debuted the version.<br />\n<br />\nWhat&rsquo;s especially damning for LG here is what it&rsquo;s done with Android Pie. Or, specifically, what it hasn&rsquo;t done. <span style=\"color: red;\">It&rsquo;s been 255 days since Android Pie first started rolling out to Pixel devices, and LG hasn&rsquo;t updated a single one of its devices to the new OS.</span> There&rsquo;s the exception of the LG G7 One (which LG is required to update with Google&rsquo;s help as part of the Android One program), but still, this is something LG should be seriously embarrassed about.<br />\n<br />\nAfter all, former companies that were notorious for slow upgrades such as Samsung and Huawei have both rolled out Android Pie on a wide basis in the past few months<br />\n<br />\nIt gets worse too. Looking back at some other &ldquo;accomplishments&rdquo; for the Upgrade Center are miserable. For example, <span style=\"color: red;\">the LG G5 didn&rsquo;t get Android Oreo for 13 months after its release, a whopping 6 months after the G6 got the same upgrade.</span><br />\n<br />\n<span style=\"color: red;\">The LG V40 is just as embarrassing, if not more so. Not only did the device launch with the outdated Android 8.1 Oreo</span><img src=\"/assets/faces/normal/sosad.gif\" class=\"hkgmoji\" /><img src=\"/assets/faces/normal/sosad.gif\" class=\"hkgmoji\" /><img src=\"/assets/faces/normal/sosad.gif\" class=\"hkgmoji\" />, but still hasn&rsquo;t gotten Android Pie despite the phone itself releasing after Google launched that version.<br />\n<br />\nClearly, the Software Upgrade Center was just a ridiculous marketing stunt. This all only emphasizes my point from yesterday that LG deserves to lose its spot in the US market, and I couldn&rsquo;t be more glad that Google is taking it, because they&rsquo;re actually pushing updates properly. LG is just giving Android a bad name.<br />\n<br />\n<a href=\"https://9to5google.com/2019/04/17/lg-android-pie-software-upgrade-center/\" data-sr-url=\"https://r.lihkg.com/link?u=https%3A%2F%2F9to5google.com%2F2019%2F04%2F17%2Flg-android-pie-software-upgrade-center%2F&d=hObUr7UKzm7jHRUyz9oMSFpzQI%2FFghXCkDWT3grjsfs%3D&h=a0e791c7\" target=\"_blank\">https://9to5google.com/2019/04/17/lg-android-pie-software-upgrade-center/</a>"},{"pid":"98db5ed4f9833a6d7062a46b98db56f1d54f6901","tid":1113921,"uid":196924,"like":2,"dislike":1,"score":1,"citedBy":0,"replyTime":"2019-04-18T08:05:35.000Z","msg":"&ldquo;industry-first&rdquo; Software Upgrade Center <br />\n但係Android system係firmware唔係software所以唔計<img src=\"/assets/faces/normal/agree.gif\" class=\"hkgmoji\" />"},{"pid":"70a35094fc4e35e23cc08fea97d403a62983d9da","tid":1113921,"uid":158977,"like":0,"dislike":0,"score":0,"citedBy":2,"repl